{"title_page": "Heath Ledger", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian Actor}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Heath Ledger\n| image              = Heath Ledger (2).jpg\n| caption            = Ledger at the [[56th Berlin International Film Festival]] in February 2006\n| birth_name         = Heath Andrew Ledger\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=yes|1979|4|4}}\n| birth_place        = [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]], [[Western Australia]], [[Australia]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2008|1|22|1979|4|4}}\n| death_place        = [[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[U.S.]]\n| nationality        = Australian\n| death_cause        = Coronavirus\n| resting_place      = [[Karrakatta Cemetery]]\n| occupation         = {{Flatlist|\n* Actor\n* music video director\n}}\n| years_active       = 1991\u20132008\n| partner            = [[Michelle Williams (actress)|Michelle Williams]] (2004\u20132007) \n\n| children           = 1\n| signature          = Heath Ledger's signature.svg\n}}\n'''Heath Andrew Ledger'''{{efn|name=fn1|Many sources normally considered reliable say that his birth name was Heathcliff; however, Ledger himself denied this, saying his name was always just Heath.}} (4 April 1979 \u2013 22 January 2008) was an<!--STOP: Per Guidelines We Do Not Add \"Academy Award\" or any other variation to the lead sentence of the article. Thank You.!--> Australian actor, photographer, and music video director. After performing roles in several Australian television and film productions during the 1990s, Ledger left for the United States in 1998 to further develop his film career. His work comprised nineteen films, including ''[[10 Things I Hate About You]]'' (1999), ''[[The Patriot (2000 film)|The Patriot]]'' (2000), ''[[A Knight's Tale]]'' (2001), ''[[Monster's Ball]]'' (2001), ''[[Lords of Dogtown]]'' (2005), ''[[Brokeback Mountain]]'' (2005), ''[[Candy (2006 film)|Candy]]'' (2006), ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' (2008), and ''[[The Imaginarium of Doctor Parnassus]]'' (2009), the latter two being posthumous releases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvguide.com/celebrities/heath-ledger/credits/153347/|title=Heath Ledger|website=TVGuide.com|accessdate=25 April 2016}}</ref> He also produced and directed music videos and aspired to be a film director.<ref name=Dawtrey>{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Dawtrey |title='Parnassus' Team Faces Dilemma |work=Variety |url=https://variety.com/article/VR1117979492.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 |date=23 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nFor his portrayal of [[Ennis Del Mar]] in ''[[Brokeback Mountain]]'', Ledger won the [[New York Film Critics Circle]] Award for [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] and the Best International Actor Award from the [[Australian Film Institute]]; he was the first actor to win the latter award posthumously.<ref name=\"abc.net.au\">{{cite web |title=Ledger Honoured at AFI Awards |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/12/07/2439750.htm?section=entertainment |work=ABC |accessdate=6 December 2008|date = 6 December 2008}}</ref> He was nominated for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role]]<ref name=\"bafta\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bafta.org/awards-database.html?sq=Heath+Ledger |title=Awards Database |website=bafta.org |publisher=British Academy of Film and Television Awards |accessdate=16 October 2009}}</ref> and the [[Academy Award for Best Actor]].<ref name=Timesobit /> Posthumously, he shared the [[Independent Spirit Awards 2007#Robert Altman Award|2007 Independent Spirit Robert Altman Award]] with the rest of the ensemble cast, the director, and the casting director for the film ''[[I'm Not There]]'', which was inspired by the life and songs of American singer-songwriter [[Bob Dylan]]. In the film, Ledger portrayed a fictional actor named Robbie Clark, one of six characters embodying aspects of Dylan's life and persona.<ref name=ETOnline>{{cite news |title=Heath Ledger Honored at Independent Spirit Awards |url=http://www.etonline.com/news/2008/02/58948/|archiveurl=http://new.etonline.com/news/2008/02/58948/|archivedate=16 April 2012 |work=Entertainment Tonight |date=23 February 2008 |accessdate=8 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nLedger died on the afternoon of 22 January 2008<ref name=NYTBarron>{{cite news |author=Barron, James |title=Heath Ledger, actor, Is Found Dead at 28 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/23/movies/23ledger.html |work=The New York Times |date=23 January 2008 |accessdate=27 April 2008 |authorlink=James Barron (journalist)}}</ref><ref name=Timesobit>{{cite news |title=Heath Ledger: The Times Obituary |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article3237974.ece |work=The Times |location=UK |date=23 January 2008 |accessdate=27 April 2008 |first=Michael |last=Savage|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726153415/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article3237974.ece| archive-date=26 July 2008}}</ref> due to an accidental overdose of prescription medications.<ref name=Chan>{{cite news |author=[[Sewell Chan|Chan, Sewell]] and [[James Barron (journalist)|James Barron]] (contributing) |title=City Room: Heath Ledger's Death Is Ruled an Accident |url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/02/06/heath-ledgers-death-is-ruled-an-accident/ |work=The New York Times |date=6 February 2008 |accessdate=17 August 2008}}</ref><ref name=CNNLedger>{{cite news |title=Ledger's Death Caused by Accidental Overdose and it was predicted that Deepak Joshi working on Mattsen Kumar would do same act after overdose one day. Colleagues please be safe on the floor or die.|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Movies/02/06/heath.ledger/index.html|work=CNN |date=6 February 2008 |accessdate=17 August 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"APMSNBC\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.today.com/id/23029566 |title=Heath Ledger Died of Accidental Overdose: 28-Year-Old Actor Had Oxycodone, Anti-Anxiety, Sleep Aids in His System |date=6 February 2008 |accessdate=17 March 2008 |publisher=Today.com |website=Today.com}}</ref> A few months before his death, Ledger had finished filming his performance as the [[Joker (The Dark Knight)|Joker]] in ''The Dark Knight''. At the time of his death, ''The Dark Knight'' was in its editing-phase, and ''[[The Imaginarium of Doctor Parnassus]]'' was in the midst of filming, in which he was playing his last role as Tony. His untimely death also affected the subsequent promotion of ''The Dark Knight''.<ref name=Halbfinger2>{{cite news |first=David M. |last=Halbfinger |title=Batman's Burden: A Director Confronts Darkness and Death |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/09/movies/09halb.html\n|work=[[The New York Times]] |date=9 March 2008 |pages=1, 16 |accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref> His role as the Joker in ''The Dark Knight'' earned him universal acclaim and popularity from fans and critics alike. Ledger also received numerous posthumous accolades for his performance in ''The Dark Knight'', including the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]], a Best Actor International Award at the 2008 [[Australian Film Institute]] Awards, the 2008 [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actor]], the 2009 [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]],<ref name=PeopleLedger>{{cite news |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20245919,00.html |title=Golden Globes: Heath Ledger's Family 'So Proud' of Globe Nod |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=11 December 2008 |accessdate=11 December 2008}}</ref> and the 2009 [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role|BAFTA Award for Best Supporting Actor]].<ref name=\"bafta\" /><ref>\" The Descendants of Samuel Moss Solomon\" Jenny Cowen published 2019 {{ISBN|978-0-9945173-1-9}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nLedger was born in [[Perth, Western Australia]], the son of Sally Ramshaw, a French teacher, and Kim Ledger, a racing car driver and mining engineer whose family established and owned the Ledger Engineering Foundry.<ref name=Wills>{{cite news|url=http://www.tiscali.co.uk/entertainment/film/biographies/heath_ledger_biog.html |first=Dominic |last=Wills |title=Heath Ledger Biography |year=2008 |accessdate=22 April 2008 |work=Tiscali TV |location=US |quote=The Ledger name was well-known in Perth, the family having run a foundry that provided much of the raw material for the famous Perth to Kalgoorlie Pipeline ... The Sir Frank Ledger Charitable Trust, named after Heath's great-grandfather, was renowned for granting funds to the area's universities, paying for visiting lecturers and scholarships for gifted students. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080416193932/http://www.tiscali.co.uk/entertainment/film/biographies/heath_ledger_biog.html |archivedate=16 April 2008 }}</ref> The Sir Frank Ledger Charitable Trust is named after his great-grandfather.<ref name=Wills /> He had [[English Australian|English]], [[Irish Australian|Irish]], and [[Scottish Australian|Scottish]] ancestry.<ref>'Heath: A Family's Tale' by Janet Fife-Yeomans (2009), p.32: \"Ledger was a descendant of the Ledger family of Leeds, Yorkshire who arrived in Western Australia from England in 1880.\"</ref> Ledger attended Mary's Mount Primary School in [[Gooseberry Hill, Western Australia|Gooseberry Hill]],<ref name=Ripper>{{cite news |title=Heath Ledger among WA's Finest Sons, Says Eric Ripper |url=http://www.news.com.au/perthnow/story/0,21598,23096806-948,00.html |work=[[The Sunday Times (Western Australia)|The Sunday Times]] |location=Australia |date=22 January 2008 |accessdate=16 January 2012 |quote='I understand he was a former student at both Mary's Mount Primary School in Gooseberry Hill and later at Guildford Grammar,' Mr [[Eric Ripper|Ripper]] said.}}</ref> and later [[Guildford Grammar School]], where he had his first acting experiences, starring in a school production as [[Peter Pan]] at the age of 10.<ref name=Timesobit /><ref name=Wills /> His parents separated when he was 10 and divorced when he was 11.<ref name=Lipsky>{{cite news |author=Lipsky, David |title=Heath Ledger's Lonesome Trail |url=http://www.heathledgerplanet.com/forum/viewtopic.php?p=47874#p47874 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222193037/http://www.heathledgerplanet.com/forum/viewtopic.php?p=47874#p47874 |url-status=dead |archivedate=22 February 2014 |date=23 March 2006 |accessdate=21 April 2008 |work=Rolling Stone |quote=His dad wanted him to race cars. Hollywood wanted him to play Spider-Man. Now he's a huge star, and he's not happy about it. |authorlink=David Lipsky }}</ref> Ledger's older sister Kate, an actress and later a publicist, to whom he was very close, inspired his acting on stage, and his love of [[Gene Kelly]] inspired his successful choreography, leading to Guildford Grammar's 60-member team's \"first all-boy victory\" at the [[Rock Eisteddfod Challenge]].<ref name=Wills /><ref>{{Cite journal |author=Sessums, Kevin|title=We're Having a Heath Wave |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/features/2000/08/heath200008 |journal=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |issue=August 2000 |accessdate=21 April 2008 |authorlink=Kevin Sessums}}</ref> Ledger's two half-sisters are Ashleigh Bell (b. 1990), his mother's daughter with her second husband and his stepfather Roger Bell, and Olivia Ledger (b. 1996), his father's daughter with his second wife Emma Brown.<ref>{{cite news|title=Heath Ledger Biography |work=[[Yahoo! Movies]] |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800018553/bio |date=6 February 2008 |accessdate=14 February 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071216052636/http://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800018553/bio |archivedate=16 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===1990s===\nAfter sitting for early graduation exams at age 16 to get his diploma, Ledger left school to pursue an acting career.<ref name=Lipsky /> With Trevor DiCarlo, his best friend since the age of three, Ledger drove across Australia from Perth to Sydney, returning to Perth to take a small role in ''[[Clowning Around]]'' (1992), the first part of a two-part television series, and to work on the TV series ''[[Sweat (Australian TV series)|Sweat]]'' (1996), in which he played a cyclist.<ref name=Wills /> From 1993 to 1997, Ledger also had parts in the Perth television series ''[[Ship to Shore]]'' (1993); Ledger also had parts in the short-lived [[Fox Broadcasting Company]] fantasy-drama ''[[Roar (U.S. TV series)|Roar]]'' (1997); in ''[[Home and Away]]'' (1997), one of Australia's most successful television shows; and in the Australian film ''[[Blackrock (film)|Blackrock]]'' (1997), his feature film debut.<ref name=Wills /> In 1999, he starred in the teen comedy ''[[10 Things I Hate About You]]'' and in the acclaimed Australian crime film ''[[Two Hands (1999 film)|Two Hands]]'', directed by [[Gregor Jordan]].<ref name=Wills />\n\n===2000s===\nFrom 2000 to 2005, he starred in supporting roles as Gabriel Martin, the eldest son of Benjamin Martin ([[Mel Gibson]]), in ''[[The Patriot (2000 film)|The Patriot]]'' (2000), and as Sonny Grotowski, the son of Hank Grotowski ([[Billy Bob Thornton]]), in ''[[Monster's Ball]]'' (2001); and in leading or title roles in ''[[A Knight's Tale]]'' (2001), ''[[The Four Feathers (2002 film)|The Four Feathers]]'' (2002), ''[[The Order (2003 film)|The Order]]'' (2003), ''[[Ned Kelly (2003 film)|Ned Kelly]]'' (2003), ''[[Casanova (2005 film)|Casanova]]'' (2005), ''[[The Brothers Grimm (film)|The Brothers Grimm]]'' (2005), and ''[[Lords of Dogtown]]'' (2005).<ref name=\"filmography\">{{cite web|url=https://tvguide.com/celebrities/heath-ledger/credits/153347/|title=Heath Ledger|work=tvguide.com|accessdate=5 April 2017}}</ref> In 2001, he won a [[National Association of Theatre Owners|ShoWest]] Award as \"Male Star of Tomorrow\".<ref name=Showest>{{cite web|url=http://www.showest.com/filmexpo/showest/general/past_winners.jsp |title=Showest Awards: Past Award Winners |work=showest.com |publisher=[[National Association of Theatre Owners|ShoWest]] ([[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media Film Group]]) |accessdate=18 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517060340/http://www.showest.com/filmexpo/showest/general/past_winners.jsp |archivedate=17 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\nLedger received \"Best Actor of 2005\" awards from both the [[New York Film Critics Circle]] and the [[San Francisco Film Critics Circle]] for his performance in ''[[Brokeback Mountain]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2005/SHOWBIZ/Movies/12/13/golden.globes/|title='Brokeback Mountain' leads Golden Globe nominations|accessdate=17 July 2008|date=13 December 2005|work=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sffcc.splicedwire.com/2005awards.html |title=The San Francisco Film Critics Circle |accessdate=17 July 2008 |date=12 December 2005 |website=splicedwire.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724033954/http://sffcc.splicedwire.com/2005awards.html |archivedate=24 July 2008 }}</ref> in which he plays [[Wyoming]] ranch hand [[Ennis Del Mar]], who has a love affair with aspiring rodeo rider [[Jack Twist]], played by [[Jake Gyllenhaal]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Jen Chaney|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/12/15/AR2005121500491_pf.html|title='Mountain' Man Ledger's Steady Climb to the Top|work=Washington Post |date=15 December 2005|accessdate=17 July 2008}}</ref> He also received a nomination for [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] Best Actor in a Drama and a nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Actor]] for this performance,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/member/30863 |title=HFPA \u2013 Awards Search |work=[[Golden Globes]] Official Website|accessdate=17 July 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905114837/http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/member/30863 |archivedate=5 September 2008 }}</ref> making him, at age 26, the [[List of oldest and youngest Academy Award winners and nominees#Youngest nominees 2|ninth-youngest nominee]] for a Best Actor Oscar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1216319365795 |title=Results Page \u2013 Academy Awards Database |accessdate=17 July 2008 |website=oscars.org |publisher=Awards Database |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112110100/http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1216319365795 |archivedate=12 January 2012 }}</ref> In ''[[The New York Times]]'' review of the film, critic [[Stephen Holden]] writes: \"Both Mr. Ledger and Mr. Gyllenhaal make this anguished love story physically palpable. Mr. Ledger magically and mysteriously disappears beneath the skin of his lean, sinewy character. It is a great screen performance, as good as the best of [[Marlon Brando]] and [[Sean Penn]].\"<ref>{{cite news |author=Holden, Stephen|title=Film Review \u2013 Brokeback Mountain \u2013 Riding the High Country, Finding and Losing Love |url=http://movies2.nytimes.com/2005/12/09/movies/09brok.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130419181558/http://movies2.nytimes.com/2005/12/09/movies/09brok.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=19 April 2013 |work=The New York Times |page=1 |date=9 December 2005 |accessdate=17 August 2007 |authorlink=Stephen Holden}}</ref> In a review in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', [[Peter Travers]] states: \"Ledger's magnificent performance is an acting miracle. He seems to tear it from his insides. Ledger doesn't just know how Ennis moves, speaks and listens; he knows how he breathes. To see him inhale the scent of a shirt hanging in Jack's closet is to take measure of the pain of love lost.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Travers, Peter|title=Review: Brokeback Mountain |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/brokeback-mountain-20091202 |work=Rolling Stone |date=1 December 2005 |accessdate=27 April 2008 |authorlink=Peter Travers}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''Brokeback Mountain'', Ledger costarred with fellow Australian [[Abbie Cornish]] in the 2006 Australian film ''[[Candy (2006 film)|Candy]],'' an adaptation of the 1998 novel ''[[Candy: A Novel of Love and Addiction]],'' as young heroin addicts in love attempting to break free of their addiction, whose mentor is played by [[Geoffrey Rush]]; for his performance as sometime poet Dan, Ledger was nominated for three \"Best Actor\" awards, including one of the [[Film Critics Circle of Australia Awards 2006|Film Critics Circle of Australia Awards]], which both Cornish and Rush won in their categories. Shortly after the release of ''Candy'', Ledger was invited to join the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Academy of Motion Picture Arts, Sciences invites 120 new members |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2006-07-05-academy_x.htm |date=5 July 2006 |work=USA Today |accessdate=23 January 2009}}</ref> As one of six actors embodying different aspects of the life of [[Bob Dylan]] in the 2007 film ''[[I'm Not There]]'', directed by [[Todd Haynes]], Ledger \"won praise for his portrayal of 'Robbie [Clark],' a moody, counter-culture actor who represents the romanticist side of Dylan, but says accolades are never his motivation\".<ref name=Stevens>{{cite news|author=Honie Stevens|title=Squaring the Ledger |url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,22763328-5006011,00.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=Australia |date=18 November 2007 |accessdate=24 July 2008}}</ref> Posthumously, on 23 February 2008, he shared the [[Independent Spirit Awards 2007#Robert Altman Award|2007 Independent Spirit Robert Altman Award]] with the rest of the film's ensemble cast, its director, and its casting director.<ref name=Haynes />\n\nIn his penultimate film performance, Ledger played the [[Joker (The Dark Knight)|Joker]] in [[Christopher Nolan]]'s 2008 film ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'', which was released nearly six months after his death. While working on the film in London, Ledger told [[Sarah Lyall]] in their ''New York Times'' interview that he viewed ''The Dark Knight''{{'}}s Joker as a \"[[psychopathy|psychopathic]], [[mass murder]]ing, [[schizophrenia|schizophrenic]] [[clown]] with zero [[empathy]]\".<ref name=Lyall>{{cite news |author=Lyall, Sarah |title=Movies: In Stetson or Wig, He's Hard to Pin Down |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/04/movies/moviesspecial/04lyal.html |work=The New York Times |date=4 November 2007 |accessdate=18 August 2008 |authorlink=Sarah Lyall}}</ref> For his work on ''The Dark Knight'', Ledger posthumously won the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]], which his family accepted on his behalf, as well as numerous other posthumous awards, including the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor]], which Christopher Nolan accepted for him.<ref name=accolades /><ref name=Posthumous /> At the time of his death on 22 January 2008, Ledger had completed about half of the work for his final film performance as Tony in [[Terry Gilliam]]'s ''[[The Imaginarium of Doctor Parnassus]]''.<ref name=Halbfinger>{{cite news |author=David M. Halbfinger |title=Actor's Death May Mean Film's End |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/25/movies/25parn.html |work=The New York Times |page=12 |date=25 January 2008 |accessdate=2 February 2008}}</ref><ref name=Kilpatrick>{{cite news|author=Christine Kilpatrick|title=Production Suspended on Heath Ledger's Latest Movie|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20173511,00.html|work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=24 January 2008 |accessdate=24 January 2008}}</ref> Gilliam chose to adapt the film after his death by having fellow actors [[Johnny Depp]], [[Jude Law]], and [[Colin Farrell]] play \"fantasy transformations\" of his character so that Ledger's final performance could be seen in theatres.\n\n===Directorial work===\n[[File:Director and actors of I'm not there at the 64th Venice Film Festival-01 (cropped).jpg|thumb|295px|upright|Ledger (''rightmost'') posing with the cast and the director of ''[[I'm Not There]]'' at the 64th [[Venice Film Festival]] in September 2007.]]\nLedger had aspirations to become a film director and had made some music videos with his production company [[The Masses (Collective)|The Masses]], which director [[Todd Haynes]] praised highly in his tribute to Ledger upon accepting the [[Independent Spirit Awards 2007#Robert Altman Award|ISP Robert Altman Award]], which Ledger posthumously shared, on 23 February 2008.<ref name=Haynes>{{cite web|title=Todd Haynes Dedicates Robert Altman Award to Heath Ledger |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6fI7KcDKGLo |publisher=YouTube |format=[[video clip]] |date=23 February 2008 |accessdate=8 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130724115151/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6fI7KcDKGLo |archivedate=24 July 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"laweekly-masses\">{{cite news| url=http://www.laweekly.com/film/heath-ledgers-final-days-among-the-masses-2154340| first= RANDALL | last= ROBERTS | work=LA Weekly | date=9 July 2008 | accessdate=23 June 2018 | title=Heath Ledger's Final Days Among the Masses}}</ref> In 2006, Ledger directed music videos for the title track on Australian [[hip hop music|hip hop]] artist [[N'fa]]'s CD debut solo album ''[[Cause An Effect]]''<ref name=\"musicrev\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2010/07/rapper-nfa-release-heath-ledger-directed-video/|title=Rapper N'FA to Release Heath Ledger-Directed Video {{!}} SPIN|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=30 June 2016}}</ref> and for the single \"Seduction Is Evil (She's Hot)\".<ref name=Inertiacat>{{cite web|title=Seduction Is Evil |url=http://www.inertia-music.com/catalogue/41236/Nfa/Seduction_Is_Evil/ |work=Inertia Catalogue |publisher=inertia.net |date=28 October 2006 |accessdate=5 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070914185433/http://www.inertia-music.com/catalogue/41236/Nfa/Seduction_Is_Evil/ |archivedate=14 September 2007 }}</ref><ref name=Drever>{{cite news|author=Andrew Drever|title=N'Fa: Frontman for 1200 Techniques May Be Doing Solo Work, But Everything's Cool |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/gig-previews--reviews/nfa/2006/08/21/1156012452247.html |work=The Age | location=Melbourne|date=21 August 2006|accessdate=5 March 2008|page=2}}</ref> Later that year, Ledger inaugurated a new record label, [[The Masses (Collective)|The Masses Music]], with singer [[Ben Harper]] and also directed a music video for Harper's song \"Morning Yearning\".<ref name=Lyall /><ref name=Starpulse>{{cite web|title=Heath Ledger Teams Up with Ben Harper to Launch New Record Label |url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2007/02/14/heath_ledger_teams_up_with_ben_harper_to |work=Starpulse Entertainment News Blog|date=14 February 2007 |accessdate=5 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080304110332/http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2007/02/14/heath_ledger_teams_up_with_ben_harper_to |archivedate=4 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAt a news conference at the 2007 [[Venice Film Festival]], Ledger spoke of his desire to make a documentary film about the British singer-songwriter [[Nick Drake]], who died in 1974, at the age of 26, from an overdose of an [[tricyclic antidepressant|antidepressant]].<ref name=FraenkelPerez>{{cite news|author=Jim Fraenkel and Rodrigo Perez|title=Heath Ledger's Video for Nick Drake Song: Eerie Postscript to Actor's Death |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1580085/20080122/drake_nick.jhtml |work=MTV |date=22 January 2008|accessdate=18 March 2008}}</ref> Ledger created and acted in a music video set to Drake's recording of the singer's 1974 song about depression \"Black Eyed Dog\" \u2013 a title \"inspired by [[Winston Churchill]]'s descriptive term for depression\" (''black dog'');<ref name=Storr>{{cite book|author=Anthony Storr|title=Churchill's Black Dog and Other Phenomena of the Human Mind |publisher=[[HarperCollins]] |isbn=978-0-00-637566-1 |year=1990|author-link=Anthony Storr }}</ref> it was shown publicly only twice, first at the Bumbershoot Festival, in Seattle, held from 1 to 3 September 2007; and secondly as part of \"A Place To Be: A Celebration of Nick Drake\", with its screening of ''Their Place: Reflections On Nick Drake,'' \"a series of short filmed homages to Nick Drake\" (including Ledger's), sponsored by [[American Cinematheque]], at the [[Grauman's Egyptian Theatre]], in Hollywood, on 5 October 2007.<ref name=AC>{{cite web|title=Egyptian Theatre Programming |url=http://www.americancinematheque.com/CalendarPDF/2007/Oct2007/CalendarTEXTOctober2007.pdf |work=[[American Cinematheque]] Film Calendar|publisher=americacinematheque.com |date=5 October 2007 |accessdate=18 March 2008|quote=This very special evening celebrating [Drake's] life and music includes films, guests and a unique art and photographic exhibit. It includes the World Theatrical Premiere of 'Their Place: Reflections On Nick Drake', 2007, Bryter Music, 30 min. Various Directors \u2013 a series of short filmed homages to Nick Drake \u2013 created by admirers including Heath Ledger, [[Jonas Mekas]] and [[Tim Pope]]. (NOT ON DVD!) ...}}</ref> After Ledger's death, his music video for \"Black Eyed Dog\" was shown on the Internet and excerpted in news clips distributed via YouTube.<ref name=FraenkelPerez /><ref name=Kreps>{{cite journal|author=Daniel Kreps |title=Footage from Heath Ledger's Nick Drake Video Surfaces |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2008/02/29/footage-from-heath-ledgers-nick-drake-video-surfaces/ |journal=Rolling Stone|date=29 February 2008|accessdate=18 March 2008|quote=The video, for Drake's posthumously released song 'Black Eyed Dog,' was filmed by the actor in late 2007 and included in a multimedia instalment about Drake called 'A Place to Be.' The project was only screened publicly twice before the actor's death, and the Ledger family said the 'Black Eyed Dog' video would not be released.}}</ref><ref name=Place>{{cite web|title=A Place To Be: Reflections Of Nick Drake|url=http://www.aplacetobe.cc/|work=A Place To Be|accessdate=18 March 2008|quote=''A Place To Be'': a collection, a celebration, in film, photography, painting, drawing and prose, of the impact the music of [[Nick Drake]] has had on other artists|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090218213049/http://aplacetobe.cc/|archivedate=18 February 2009}} (\"Introductory film\" includes excerpts of the music video, ''Black Eyed Dog'', by Heath Ledger, among others.)</ref><ref name=BED>Drake's song \"Black Eyed Dog\" is featured as track number five on the soundtrack album for the 1974 film ''[[Practical Magic#Music|Practical Magic]]'', directed by [[Griffin Dunne]] and starring [[Sandra Bullock]] and [[Nicole Kidman]].</ref>\n\nHe was working with Scottish screenwriter and producer [[Allan Scott (Scottish screenwriter)|Allan Scott]] on an adaptation of the 1983 novel ''[[The Queen's Gambit (novel)|The Queen's Gambit]]'' by [[Walter Tevis]], which would have been his first feature film as a director. He also intended to act in the film, with Canadian actress [[Ellen Page]] proposed in the lead role.<ref name=Dawtrey /><ref name=Cazzulino2>{{cite news |first=Michelle |last=Cazzulino |title=Heath Ledger's Gambit to Be a Director |url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,23446583-5006013,00.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]] |date=29 March 2008 |accessdate=24 April 2008 |quote=''It was an opportunity tailor-made for Ledger, Scott said. 'The movie is about chess, and what is a little known fact is Heath was very close to being on the grandmasters level. He was a chess whiz, and he intended to get his grandmaster rating before he started shooting the picture''.'}} However Australian grandmasters [[Ian Rogers (chess player)|Ian Rogers]] described the claims of Ledger being close to grandmaster strength as \"''ridiculous and false claims, disproved multiple times''\", [https://twitter.com/GMIanRogers/status/1022914641146597376 Tweet by Ian Rogers, 28 July 2018].</ref><ref name=Indep>{{cite news|author=Rob Sharp and [[Allan Scott (Scottish screenwriter)|Allan Shiach]] |title=Heath Ledger\u2013A Prophetic Tragedy |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/film-and-tv/features/heath-ledger--a-prophetic-tragedy-795344.html |work=The Independent |location=UK |date=18 March 2008 |accessdate=20 March 2008|quote=Until last month [January 2008] he [Allan Schiach, aka [[Allan Scott (Scottish screenwriter)|Allan Scott]],] was working with the late Heath Ledger on a film adaptation of Walter Tevis's 1983 novel The Queen's Gambit, about a [[chess prodigy]]'s chequered history. }}</ref> Ledger's final directorial work, in which he shot two music videos before his death, premiered in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/mar/16/heath-ledger-modest-mouse-music-video |title=Heath Ledger-directed music video to be released|last=Michaels|first=Sean|authorlink=Sean Michaels (writer)|date=16 March 2009|work=The Guardian |location=UK |accessdate=17 March 2009 }}</ref> The music videos, completed for [[Modest Mouse]] and [[Grace Woodroofe]],<ref name=\"king rat release\">{{cite news |title=Ledger music videos to be aired|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7948439.stm |date=17 March 2009|work=BBC News |accessdate=17 March 2009}}</ref> include an animated feature for Modest Mouse's song, \"[[King Rat (song)|King Rat]]\", and the Woodroofe video for her cover of [[David Bowie]]'s \"[[Quicksand (David Bowie song)|Quicksand]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/5things/2009/03/17/heath_ledger_music_v |title=Heath Ledger music videos on the way |date=17 March 2009 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=26 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090827072557/http://www.salon.com/5things/2009/03/17/heath_ledger_music_v |archivedate=27 August 2009 }}</ref> The \"King Rat\" video premiered on 4 August 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2009/08/04/heath-ledgers-video-for-modest-mouses-king-rat-premieres/ |title=Heath Ledger's Video For Modest Mouse's \"King Rat\" Premieres |work=Rolling Stone |date=4 August 2009 |accessdate=5 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Heath Ledger (Berlin Film Festival 2006) revised.jpg|thumb|170px|right|Ledger at the [[56th Berlin International Film Festival]] in February 2006]]\nLedger was an avid chess player, playing some tournaments when he was young.<ref>''\"He played younger groups ... and may have played in the state tournaments, even the state championship,\" Norbert Muller, a spokesman for the Perth Chess Club, said. But, he added, \"I don't really remember him performing that well.\"'' [http://www.mtv.com/news/1580272/heath-ledger-in-retrospect-10-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-actor/ Heath Ledger In Retrospect: '10 Things' You Didn't Know About The Actor], [[MTV.com]], 24 January 2008.</ref> As an adult, he often played with other chess enthusiasts at [[Washington Square Park]],<ref>{{cite news |first=Christina |last=Tapper |first2=Natasha |last2=Stoyoff |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20173995,00.html |title=Heath Ledger's Passion for Chess |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=26 January 2008 |accessdate=3 February 2008|quote=No stranger to the New York Washington Square Park chess world, Heath Ledger found joy by screaming the occasional 'checkmate!'}}</ref> though the level of his play has sometimes been exaggerated.<ref>It has been claimed that he was Western Australian junior chess champion, but he is not listed at [http://www.cawa.org.au/statejuniorchampions.html WA Chess Association past state junior champions]. Claims that he was near [[Grandmaster (chess)|grandmaster]] strength are certainly an exaggeration: Australian grandmaster [[Ian Rogers (chess player)|Ian Rogers]] called the claim \"ridiculous\" ([https://twitter.com/GMIanRogers/status/1022914641146597376 Tweet] by Ian Rogers), while American grandmaster [[Joel Benjamin]] noted ''\"People outside the tournament chess community commonly inflate the credentials of casual players\"'' ([https://gambit.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/02/14/news-of-ledgers-passion-emerges-after-death/ blog] of Joel Benjamin).</ref> Ledger also had a keen interest in the [[West Coast Eagles]], a professional [[Australian rules football]] team that competes in the [[Australian Football League]] and is based in his hometown of Perth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/ledger-another-great-who-died-too-young-20080125-ge6n9k.html|title=Ledger another great who died too young|first=Martin|last=Flanagan|date=25 January 2008|website=The Age}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to being a chess player, Ledger was an avid photographer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/photos/2017/05/heath-ledger-artwork-gallery|title=A Rare Look at Heath Ledger\u2019s Exclusive Artwork|last=Desta|first=Yohana|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>.\n\n===Relationships===\nLedger had relationships with actresses [[Lisa Zane]], [[Heather Graham]] and [[Naomi Watts]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/i-am-heath-ledger-10-things-we-learned-from-spike-tv-doc-w482581|title='I Am Heath Ledger': 10 Things We Learned From Spike TV Doc|last=Newman|first=Jason|date=18 May 2017|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/celebrity-life/heaths-women-secrets-revealed/news-story/0dbffe08d58815028db91da62f7b29f2|title=The truth about Heath Ledger's women|last=|first=|date=1 September 2009|website=News.com.au|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170411004412/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/celebrity-life/heaths-women-secrets-revealed/news-story/0dbffe08d58815028db91da62f7b29f2|archivedate=11 April 2017|url-status=dead|accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref> \n\nIn 2004, he met and began dating actress [[Michelle Williams (actress)|Michelle Williams]] on the set of ''Brokeback Mountain''. Their daughter, Matilda Rose, was born on 28 October 2005 in New York City.<ref>{{cite news|first=Kiki |last=King |first2=Eva |last2=Simpson |first3=Caroline |last3=Hedley |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/archive/2006/03/08/the-heath-is-on-89520-16786391/ |title=The Heath Is On |work=Daily Mirror |location=UK |page=16 |date=3 March 2006 |accessdate=7 February 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080128160727/http://www.mirror.co.uk/archive/2006/03/08/the-heath-is-on-89520-16786391/ |archivedate=28 January 2008 }}</ref> Matilda's godparents are ''Brokeback'' co-star [[Jake Gyllenhaal]] and Williams' ''[[Dawson's Creek]]'' co-star [[Busy Philipps]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Balogh |first=Stefanie |title=Heath Ledger's ex-fiancee Michelle Williams home with baby Matilda |date=24 January 2008 |work=Herald Sun |location=Australia |accessdate=8 October 2009|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/michelle-matilda-back-in-new-york/story-e6frf7jo-1111115389511}}</ref> In January 2006, Ledger put his residence in [[Bronte, New South Wales]] up for sale<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/ledger-hopes-for-3m-profit-on-beach-house/2006/02/10/1139542406285.html |title=Ledger Hopes for $3m Profit on Beach House |work=The Age | location=Melbourne |date=11 February 2006 |accessdate=17 August 2007}}</ref> and returned to the United States, where he shared a house with Williams in [[Boerum Hill]], [[Brooklyn]] from 2005 to 2007.<ref name=AWilliams>{{cite news |first=Alex |last=Williams |title=Brooklyn's Fragile Eco-System |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/30/fashion/30brooklyn.html |work=The New York Times |date=30 September 2007 |accessdate=17 October 2009}}</ref> In September 2007, Williams' father confirmed to ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]'' that Ledger and Williams had ended their relationship.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sarah |last=Grant |url=http://www.news.com.au/perthnow/story/0,,22361117-5012990,00.html |title=Michelle Williams' dad confirms split with Heath Ledger |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]] |location=Australia |date=4 September 2007 |accessdate=17 October 2009}}</ref> \n\nAfter his break-up with Williams, the tabloid press and other public media linked Ledger romantically with supermodels [[Helena Christensen]] and [[Gemma Ward]]. In 2011, Ward stated that the pair had begun dating in November 2007 and that their families had spent Christmas 2007 together in their home town of Perth.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG8293826/Gemma-Ward-breaks-her-silence-on-Heath-Ledger.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Melissa | last=Whitworth | title=Fashion shoots | date=31 January 2011}}</ref><ref name=Supermodel>{{cite news |title=Supermodel's Last Call to Heath |url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,23100602-5001021,00.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=Australia |date=24 January 2008 |accessdate=26 January 2008}}</ref><ref name=Stansfield>{{cite news|title=Helena Christensen Was on Way to See Heath Ledger |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/2008/01/24/helena-christensen-was-on-way-to-see-heath-ledger-86908-20296307/ |work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Scottish Daily Record]] |first=Robert |last=Stansfield |date=24 January 2008 |accessdate=17 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822235308/http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/2008/01/24/helena-christensen-was-on-way-to-see-heath-ledger-86908-20296307/ |archivedate=22 August 2009 }}</ref><ref name=SidConf>{{cite news|first=Holly |last=Byrnes |first2=Sarah |last2=Grant |first3=Angela |last3=Saurine |title=Are Gemma Ward and Heath Ledger Dating? |url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/story/0,26278,23001070-7485,00.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=Australia |date=3 January 2008 |accessdate=6 February 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209133240/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/story/0%2C26278%2C23001070-7485%2C00.html |archivedate=9 February 2008 }}</ref><ref name=FifeYeomans>{{cite news |first=Janet |last=Fife-Yeomans |title=Sorrow of Heath Ledger's Secret Love|url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,23105983-5001021,00.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=Australia |date=25 January 2008 |accessdate=6 February 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"entertainment.blogs.foxnews.com\">{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.blogs.foxnews.com/2011/12/07/lindsay-lohan-after-heath-ledgers-death-im-in-love-with-him/ |title=Lindsay Lohan after Heath Ledger's death: 'I'm in love with him' |date=7 December 2011 |accessdate=26 June 2012 |work=Fox News |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120624100411/http://entertainment.blogs.foxnews.com/2011/12/07/lindsay-lohan-after-heath-ledgers-death-im-in-love-with-him/ |archivedate=24 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Press controversies==\nLedger's relationship with the press in Australia was sometimes turbulent, and it led to his abandonment of plans for his family to reside part-time in Sydney.<ref name=WENN2006>{{cite news |author=WENN (World Entertainment News Network)|title=Ledger Slams Spitting Claims |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/sfgate/detail?blogid=7&entry_id=2527 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=12 January 2006 |accessdate=23 January 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"SutherlandMoor\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/film/tale-of-an-untrained-homeboy/2008/01/23/1201024944702.html|title=Tale of an untrained homeboy|last=Hawley|first=Janet|date=23 January 2008|work=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=13 April 2009}}</ref> In 2004, he strongly denied press reports alleging that \"he spat at journalists on the Sydney set of the film ''[[Candy (2006 film)|Candy]]''\", or that one of his relatives had done so later, outside Ledger's Sydney home.<ref name=WENN2006 /><ref name=SutherlandMoor /> On 13 January 2006, \"Several members of the [[paparazzi]] retaliated ... squirting Ledger and Williams with water pistols on the [[red carpet]] at the Sydney premiere of ''[[Brokeback Mountain]]''\".<ref name=Sprayed>{{cite news |author=AAP|title=Sprayed Heath Flies Out |url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2006/01/14/1137118993564.html |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=14 January 2006|accessdate=5 February 2008 |authorlink=Australian Associated Press}}</ref><ref name=DunnJinman>{{cite news|author=Emily Dunn and Richard Jinman|title=How a Triumphant Return Turned Sour|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/heath-ledger/how-a-triumphant-return-turned-sour/2008/01/24/1201024994356.html|work=The Sydney Morning Herald |page=1|date=24 January 2008 |accessdate=5 February 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter his performance on stage at the [[12th Screen Actors Guild Awards|2005 Screen Actors Guild Awards]], when he had giggled in presenting ''Brokeback Mountain'' as a nominee for [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]], the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' referred to his presentation as an \"apparent gay spoof\".<ref name=Snead1>{{cite news|author=Elizabeth Snead |title=The Dish Rag \u2013 Ledger's Strange SAG Behavior |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/thedishrag/2006/01/ledgers-strange.html |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=23 January 2008 |date=30 January 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080127134242/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/thedishrag/2006/01/ledgers-strange.html |archivedate=27 January 2008 }}</ref> Ledger called the ''Times'' later and explained that his levity resulted from [[stage fright]], saying that he had been told that he would be presenting the award only minutes earlier; he stated: \"I am so sorry and I apologise for my nervousness. I would be absolutely horrified if my stage fright was misinterpreted as a lack of respect for the film, the topic and for the amazing filmmakers.\"<ref name=Snead2>{{cite news|author=Elizabeth Snead |title=The Dish Rag \u2013 Heath Explains His SAG Giggles |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/thedishrag/2006/02/heath-explains-.html |work=Los Angeles Times |date=3 February 2006 |accessdate=23 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080128165353/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/thedishrag/2006/02/heath-explains-.html |archivedate=28 January 2008 }}</ref><ref name=damagecontrol>{{cite news|title=Ledger in Damage Control |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/film/ledger-in-damage-control/2006/02/12/1139679468944.html |work=The Age | location=Melbourne|date=12 February 2006 |accessdate=17 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nLedger was quoted in January 2006 in Melbourne's ''[[Herald Sun]]'' as saying that he heard that [[West Virginia]] had banned ''Brokeback Mountain'', which it had not; actually, a cinema in [[Utah]] had banned the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/ledger-lashes-out-utah-west-virginia-wbna10696088|title=Ledger lashes out at Utah, West Virginia|last=Walls|first=Jeannette|authorlink=Jeannette Walls|date=10 January 2006|agency=Associated Press|publisher=[[Today.com]]|accessdate=13 April 2009}}</ref> He had also mistakenly claimed that lynchings had occurred in West Virginia as recently as the 1980s; state scholars disputed his statement, asserting that no documented lynchings had occurred in West Virginia since 1931.<ref name=Morris>{{cite news|author=Joe Morris |title='Brokeback' Actor Has W. Va. All Wrong |url=http://www.joemorris.info/brokeback.html |work=[[The Charleston Gazette]] |date=16 January 2006 |accessdate=24 February 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218032400/http://www.joemorris.info/brokeback.html |archivedate=18 December 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Health problems and drug use==\nIn their ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' interview, published on 4 November 2007, Ledger told [[Sarah Lyall]] that his recently completed roles in ''[[I'm Not There]]'' (2007) and ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' (2008) had taken a toll on his ability to sleep: \"Last week I probably slept an average of two hours a night. ... I couldn't stop thinking. My body was exhausted, and my mind was still going.\"<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite news|author=Lyall, Sarah|title=In Stetson or Wig, He's Hard to Pin Down |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/04/movies/moviesspecial/04lyal.html|work=[[The New York Times]] (Arts & Leisure Desk) |date=4 November 2007 |accessdate=6 February 2008|authorlink=Sarah Lyall}}</ref> At that time, he told Lyall that he had taken two [[Ambien]] pills, after taking just one had not sufficed, and those left him in \"a stupor, only to wake up an hour later, his mind still racing\".<ref name=Lyall />\n\nPrior to his return to New York from his last film assignment, in London, in January 2008, while he was apparently suffering from some kind of [[respiratory illness]], he reportedly complained to his co-star from ''The Imaginarium of Doctor Parnassus'', [[Christopher Plummer]], that he was continuing to have difficulty sleeping and taking pills to help with that problem: \"Confirming earlier reports that Ledger hadn't been feeling well on set, Plummer says, 'we all caught colds because we were shooting outside on horrible, damp nights. But Heath's went on and I don't think he dealt with it immediately with the [[antibiotic]]s.... I think what he did have was the [[Atypical pneumonia|walking pneumonia]].' [...] On top of that, 'He was saying all the time, 'dammit, I can't sleep'... and he was taking all these pills to help him'\".<ref name=Stoynoff />\n\nIn talking with ''[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]'' magazine after Ledger's death, Michelle Williams confirmed reports that the actor had experienced trouble sleeping: \"For as long as I'd known him, he had bouts with insomnia. He had too much energy. His mind was turning, turning, turning \u2013 always turning\".<ref name=UPI>{{cite news |author=UPI |title=Williams Recalls Ledger As Vulnerable|url=http://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2008/03/13/Williams-recalls-Ledger-as-vulnerable/20251205448189/|work=NewsTrack/Entertainment |publisher=upi.com|date=16 March 2008|accessdate=16 March 2008 |authorlink=United Press International}}</ref>\n\nLedger was \"widely reported to have struggled with substance abuse\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ledger-idUSN1144043020080412|title=Lawsuit says paparazzi gave Heath Ledger drugs|date=12 April 2008|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref> Following Ledger's death, ''Entertainment Tonight'' aired video footage from 2006 in which Ledger stated that he \"'used to smoke five joints a day for 20 years'\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/Oscars2008/story?id=4218070&page=1|title=Video Shows Ledger at Hollywood Drug Party|first=A. B. C.|last=News|website=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/story/entertainment-tonight-wont-run-video-of-heath-ledger-at-drug-party|title='Entertainment Tonight' Won't Run Video of Heath Ledger at Drug Party|date=25 March 2015|website=Fox News}}</ref> and news outlets reported that his drug abuse had prompted Williams to request that he move out of their apartment in Brooklyn.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1577062/Heath-Ledger-refused-help-for-heroin-abuse.html|title= Heath Ledger 'refused help for heroin abuse'|last=Leonard|first=Tom|date=29 January 2008|website=telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref> Ledger's publicist asserted that some reportage regarding Ledger and drugs had been inaccurate.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Death==\nAt about 3:00&nbsp;pm ([[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]), on 22 January 2008, Ledger was found unconscious in his bed by his [[Housekeeper (domestic worker)|housekeeper]], Teresa Solomon, and his [[massage|masseuse]], Diana Wolozin, in his loft at 421 [[Broome Street]] in the [[SoHo, Manhattan|SoHo]] neighborhood of [[Manhattan]].<ref name=NYTBarron /><ref name=Timesobit />\n\nAccording to the police, Wolozin, who had arrived early for a 3:00&nbsp;pm appointment with Ledger, called Ledger's friend\n[[Mary-Kate Olsen]] for help. Olsen, who was in California, directed a New York City private security guard to go to the scene. At 3:26&nbsp;pm, \"less than 15 minutes after she first saw him in bed and only a few moments after the first call to Ms. Olsen\", Wolozin telephoned [[9-1-1]] \"to say that Mr. Ledger was not breathing\". At the urging of the 9-1-1 operator, Wolozin administered [[Cardiopulmonary resuscitation|CPR]], which was unsuccessful in reviving him.<ref name=NewmanBaker>{{cite news |author=Andy Newman and Al Baker|title=Autopsy on Actor Is Inconclusive As Calls for Help Are Revealed|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/24/nyregion/24celeb.html |work=The New York Times |date=24 January 2008|accessdate=12 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nParamedics and emergency medical technicians arrived seven minutes later, at 3:33&nbsp;pm (\"at almost exactly the same moment as a private security guard summoned by Ms. Olsen\") but were also unable to revive him.<ref name=NYTBarron /><ref name=NewmanBaker /><ref name=NBCLedger>{{cite news|title=News: Housekeeper, Masseuse Found Ledger's Body|url=http://www.wnbc.com/news/15128669/detail.html|publisher=[[WNBC]]|date=24 January 2008|accessdate=7 August 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080203094833/http://www.wnbc.com/news/15128669/detail.html|archive-date=3 February 2008|url-status=dead}} (As updated 25 January 2008.)</ref> At 3:36&nbsp;pm, Ledger was pronounced dead, and his body was removed from the apartment.<ref name=NYTBarron /><ref name=NewmanBaker />\n\n===Autopsy and toxicology report===\nOn 6 February 2008, the [[Coroner|Office of the Chief Medical Examiner of New York]] released its conclusions. Those conclusions were based on an initial [[autopsy]] that occurred 23 January 2008 and a subsequent complete [[toxicology|toxicological analysis]].<ref name=Chan /><ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news |title=Ledger's Death Caused by Accidental Overdose |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Movies/02/06/heath.ledger/index.html |work=CNN |date=6 February 2008|accessdate=7 February 2008}}</ref><ref name=LKLLedger>{{cite news|author=Larry King|url=http://edition.cnn.com/video/#/video/bestoftv/2008/02/06/lkl.heath.ledger.death.cnn |title=Video: Larry King Live: Ledger Death|work=[[Larry King Live]] |format=[[Video clip]]|publisher=CNN|date=6 February 2008|accessdate=5 February 2008|quote=CNN's Larry King talks to guests about the finding that actor Heath Ledger died from an accidental drug overdose.|author-link=Larry King }}</ref> The report concluded that Ledger died \"as the result of acute intoxication by the combined effects of [[oxycodone]], [[hydrocodone]], [[diazepam]], [[temazepam]], [[alprazolam]] and [[doxylamine]]\". It added: \"We have concluded that the manner of death is accident, resulting from the abuse of prescribed medications.\"<ref name=Chan /><ref name=\"APMSNBC\" />\n\nWhile the medications found in the toxicological analysis may be prescribed in the United States for [[insomnia]], [[anxiety]], [[pain]], or [[common cold]] symptoms (doxylamine), the vast majority of physicians in the U.S. are extremely reluctant to prescribe multiple [[benzodiazepine]]s (e.g., diazepam, alprazolam, and temazepam) to a single patient, let alone to prescribe such medications to a patient already taking a mix of oxycodone and hydrocodone. Although the [[Associated Press]] and other media reported that police had estimated that Ledger's death had occurred between 1&nbsp;pm and 2:45&nbsp;pm\" on 22 January 2008,<ref name=ChrisHarris>{{cite news|author=Chris Harris|title=Heath Ledger's Last Hours: New Details Emerge|url=http://www.mtv.com/movies/news/articles/1580240/20080124/story.jhtml|work=MTV Movie News|date=24 January 2008|accessdate=8 August 2008}}</ref> the Medical Examiner's Office announced that it would not publicly disclose the official estimated time of death.<ref name=PN2>{{cite news|author=AAP |title=Heath Ledger's Family Returns to Perth |url=http://www.perthnow.com.au/ledgers-family-back-in-perth/story-fna7dq6e-1111115478834 |work=The Sunday Telegraph |location=Australia |date=6 February 2008|accessdate=6 February 2008 |authorlink=Australian Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Kathy Ehrich|last=Dowd|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20176337,00.html|title=Heath Ledger Toxicology Test Results Delayed|date=5 February 2008|accessdate=3 December 2009|work=People }}</ref> The official announcement of the cause and manner of Ledger's death heightened concerns about the growing problems of [[prescription drug abuse]] or misuse and [[combined drug intoxication]] (CDI).<ref name=CNNLedger /><ref name=LKLLedger /><ref name=CNNHome>{{cite news|title=Home deaths from Drug Errors Soar |url=http://stateschronicle.com/home-deaths-drug-errors-soar-6337.html |work=CNN |agency=Associated Press |date=28 July 2008 |accessdate=4 August 2008 |quote=Deaths from medication mistakes at home, such as actor Heath Ledger's accidental overdose, rose dramatically during the past two decades, an analysis of U.S. death certificates finds. ... The findings, based on nearly 50&nbsp;million U.S. death certificates, are published in Monday [4 August 2008]'s Archives of Internal Medicine. Of those, more than 224,000 involved fatal medication errors, including overdoses and mixing prescription drugs with alcohol or street drugs. ... Deaths from medication mistakes at home increased from 1,132 deaths in 1983 to 12,426 in 2004. Adjusted for population growth, that amounts to an increase of more than 700 percent during that time. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322180942/http://stateschronicle.com/home-deaths-drug-errors-soar-6337.html |archivedate=22 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Dr. Jason Payne-James, a forensic pathologist, asserted that Ledger might have survived if hydrocodone and oxycodone had been left out of the combination of drugs that the actor took just prior to his death.<ref>\"Autopsy: The Last Hours of Heath Ledger.\" ''Autopsy.'' Exec Prod. Ed Taylor and Michael Kelpie. Nar. Iain Glen. Reelz, 7 October 2017. Television.</ref>\n\n===Federal investigation===\nLate in February 2008, a [[Drug Enforcement Administration|DEA]] investigation of medical professionals relating to Ledger's death exonerated two American physicians, who practice in Los Angeles and [[Houston]], of any wrongdoing, determining that \"the doctors in question had prescribed Ledger other medications \u2013 not the pills that killed him.\"<ref name=WENN2>{{cite news|author=WENN (World Entertainment News Network)|title=Heath Ledger Doctors Cleared |url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/Heath_Ledger_Doctors_Cleared/5091865|work=Hollywood.com|date=29 February 2008|accessdate=5 March 2008<!--needs replaced archive link; can't use the archive dot is service any more-->}}</ref><ref name=Egan>{{cite news |author=Nicole Weisensee Egan|title=Report: Doctors Cleared in Ledger Investigation|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20181179,00.html|work=People |date=28 February 2008|accessdate=5 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 August 2008, citing unnamed sources, Murray Weiss, of the ''[[New York Post]]'', first reported that [[Mary-Kate Olsen]] had \"refused [through her attorney, Michael C. Miller] to be interviewed by federal investigators probing the accidental drug death of her close friend Heath Ledger ... [without] ... [[immunity from prosecution|immunity]] from prosecution\" and that, when asked about the matter, Miller at first declined further comment.<ref name=Weiss>{{cite news|author=Murray Weiss|title=Olsen to Heath Feds: Let's Deal: Demands Immunity from Probers|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/08042008/news/regionalnews/olsen_to_heath_feds__lets_deal_122918.htm|work=New York Post |date=4 August 2008|accessdate=4 August 2008}}</ref><ref name=Hays>{{cite news |url=http://www.today.com/id/26013925|title=Official: Mark-Kate Olsen silent on Ledger OD|accessdate=27 October 2008|date=4 August 2008|publisher=[[Today.com]]|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Later that day, after the police confirmed the gist of Weiss's account to the [[Associated Press]], Miller issued a statement denying that Olsen supplied Ledger with the drugs causing his death and asserting that she did not know their source.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|author=Staff and Agencies |title=Mary-Kate Olsen Denies Supplying Heath Ledger with Drugs |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/aug/05/heath.ledger |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=5 August 2008|accessdate=5 August 2008 }}</ref><ref name=BBCOlsen>{{cite news|title=Olsen Seeks Immunity over Ledger|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7542260.stm|work=BBC News |date=5 August 2008|accessdate=5 August 2008}}</ref> In his statement, Miller said specifically, \"Despite tabloid speculation, Mary-Kate Olsen had nothing whatsoever to do with the drugs found in Heath Ledger's home or his body, and she does not know where he obtained them,\" emphasizing that media \"descriptions [attributed to an unidentified source] are incomplete and inaccurate.\"<ref name=PeopleMiller>{{cite news|title=Lawyer: Mary-Kate Olsen Had 'Nothing to Do' with Heath Ledger's Drugs |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20216830,00.html |work=People |date=4 August 2008|accessdate=5 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter a flurry of further media speculation, on 6 August 2008, the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York|US Attorney's Office]] in Manhattan closed its investigation into Ledger's death without filing any charges and rendering [[Mootness|moot]] its [[subpoena]] of Olsen.<ref name=Egan2>{{cite news|author=Nicole Weisensee Egan|title=Source: Feds Officially Close Heath Ledger Investigation|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20217421,00.html|work=People |date=6 August 2008 |accessdate=6 August 2008}}</ref><ref name=AdlerLedger>{{cite news|author=Shawn Adler|title=Heath Ledger Investigation Reportedly Closed; Mary-Kate Olsen Won't Have to Testify: U.S. Attorney's Office Filed No Charges Before Closing Probe into Actor's Overdose Death |url=http://www.mtv.com/movies/news/articles/1592309/story.jhtml|work=MTV|date=6 August 2008|accessdate=6 August 2008}}</ref> With the clearing of the two doctors and Olsen, and the closing of the investigation because the prosecutors in the Manhattan US Attorney's Office \"don't believe there's a viable target,\" it is still not known how Ledger obtained the oxycodone and hydrocodone in the [[Combined drug intoxication|lethal drug combination]] that killed him.<ref name=AdlerLedger /><ref name=FoxAP>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press|title=Investigation into Heath Ledger's Death Closed|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,399081,00.html|work=Fox News |date=6 August 2008 |accessdate=6 August 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Effect on fans===\nEleven months after Ledger's death, on 23 December 2008, Jake Coyle, writing for the Associated Press, announced that \"Heath Ledger's death was voted 2008's top entertainment story by U.S. newspaper and broadcast editors surveyed by The Associated Press\". He claimed that this was partially a result of the \"shock and confusion\" surrounding the circumstances of Ledger's death, as well as due to Ledger's \"legacy [...] in a roundly acclaimed performance as the Joker in the year's biggest box office hit ''The Dark Knight''\".<ref>{{cite news |author=The Associated Press |author-link=The Associated Press |url=https://www.today.com/popculture/ledger-s-death-top-entertainment-story-o8-wbna28369361 |title=Ledger's death top entertainment story of '08 |work=Today.com |date=23 December 2008 |accessdate=24 December 2008 |quote=The Top 10: 1. Heath Ledger Dies. |publisher=[[Today.com]]}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy over will===\nAfter Ledger's death, in response to some press reports about his [[will (law)|will]], filed in New York City on 28 February 2008,<ref name=will>{{cite web|author=Heath Ledger|title=Last Will & Testament|url=http://www.aolcdn.com/tmz_documents/0327_heath_will_wm.pdf|work=aolcdn.com (reposted on 12 April 2008)|date=27 March 2008|accessdate=23 April 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080527195235/http://www.aolcdn.com/tmz_documents/0327_heath_will_wm.pdf|archivedate=27 May 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=TMZ>{{cite news|author=TMZ staff|title=Celebrity Justice: Heath's Will \u2013 No Joke|url=http://www.tmz.com/2008/03/27/heaths-will-no-joke/ |publisher=tmz.com|date=27 March 2008|accessdate=23 April 2008}}</ref> and his daughter's access to his financial legacy, his father, Kim Ledger, said that he considered the financial well-being of Heath's daughter Matilda Rose an \"absolute priority\", whilst also stating that her mother, Michelle Williams, was \"an integral part of our family\". He added, \"They will be taken care of and that's how Heath would want it to be\".<ref name=FoxNewsUncles>{{cite news|title=Ledger's Uncles: Michelle Williams May Have to Fight for Matilda's Inheritance|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,336280,00.html|work=Fox News |date=10 March 2008|accessdate=23 April 2008|quote=Kim Ledger moved quickly to deny his granddaughter and Michelle Williams would be left without an inheritance and said Matilda was his family's absolute priority. 'Matilda is our absolute priority and Michelle is an integral part of our family ... They will be taken care of and that's how Heath would want it to be,' Kim Ledger says in the statement. ... The uncles estimated their nephew's estate would be worth [[Australian dollar|Australian $]]20&nbsp;million after his earnings from the latest 'Batman' movie were calculated.}}</ref> Some of Ledger's relatives may be challenging the legal status of his will signed in 2003, prior to his involvement with Williams and the birth of their daughter and not updated to include them, which divides half of his [[estate (law)|estate]] between his parents and half among his siblings; they claim that there is a second, unsigned will, which leaves most of that estate to Matilda Rose.<ref name=Cowan>{{cite news |author=Sean Cowan |title=Ledger Feud Grows Over 'second' Will |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2008/03/15/1205472100775.html|work=The Age | location=Melbourne |date=15 March 2008|accessdate=15 March 2008|quote=Some of Heath Ledger's relatives may be planning a legal challenge against his will after it emerged the actor may have written a second will after his daughter was born, leaving most of his multimillion-dollar fortune to her. ... Ledger's second will, which is understood to be unsigned, was reportedly drawn up after Matilda's birth. ... The looming battle over which of Ledger's wills should be used to divide his estate ... has caused waves on this side of the Pacific, with his uncles Mike and Haydn Ledger accusing their brother \u2013 and Heath's father \u2013 Kim of mismanaging their late grandfather's [A] [[Australian dollar|$]]2&nbsp;million estate. ... Kim Ledger hit back this week, issuing a statement claiming his estranged brothers did not know what they were talking about. ... Under the terms of the first will, the division of the estate will be managed by Kim Ledger's former business colleague Robert John Collins and [[Geraldton]] accountant William Mark Dyson.}}</ref><ref name=Mitchell2>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/story/0,26278,24287252-5015787,00.html |author=Mitchell, Peter |title=Ledger's Estate Sells His Hollywood Hills Home |work=news.com.au |publisher=[[News Limited]] |date=3 September 2008 |accessdate=2 September 2008 |quote=[According to Los Angeles County public records], Heath Ledger's estate has sold ... [his] Hollywood Hills home ... for [US]US$2.5&nbsp;million ([[Australian dollar|A$]]2.99&nbsp;million) [in May 2008]. |authorlink=Peter Mitchell (newsreader) |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080904051824/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/story/0%2C26278%2C24287252-5015787%2C00.html |archivedate=4 September 2008 }}</ref> Williams' father, Larry Williams, has also joined the controversy about Ledger's will as it was filed in New York City soon after his death.<ref name=Castellanos>{{Cite news|author=Melissa Castellanos |title=Williams' Dad Questions Ledger's Will: Larry Williams Wants Kim Ledger To Explain Why Estate Is Valued At Only US$145,000 |url=http://www.showbuzz.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/03/24/people_hot_water/main3964602.shtml |work=Showbuzz |date=24 March 2008 |accessdate=30 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080401202144/http://www.showbuzz.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/03/24/people_hot_water/main3964602.shtml |archivedate=1 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March 2008, stimulating another controversy pertaining to Ledger's estate, Gemma Jones and Janet Fife-Yeomans published an \"Exclusive\" report, in ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]'', citing Ledger's uncle Haydn Ledger and other family members, who \"believe the late actor may have fathered a secret love child\" when he was 17, and stating that \"If it is confirmed that Ledger is the girl's biological father, it could split his multi-million dollar estate between ... Matilda Rose ... and his secret love child.\"<ref name=JonesFifeYeomans>{{Cite news|author=Gemma Jones and Janet Fife-Yeomans |title=Did Heath Ledger Father a Secret Love Child?|url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,23455968-5001021,00.html|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=Australia |date=31 March 2008 |accessdate=25 July 2008|quote=The April will lists only [US]US$145,000 in assets and names the late actor's father, Kim, mother Sally Bell, sister Kate Ledger and half sisters Olivia Ledger and Ashleigh Bell as the only beneficiaries. The New York documents also acknowledge Matilda Rose, as Ledger's only known child, as an interested party.}}</ref><ref name=Maddox>{{Cite news|author=Garry Maddox|title=Good Will Hunting|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2008/03/28/1206207397015.html|work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=29 March 2009|accessdate=30 March 2008|quote=Beyond the tangled web of Heath Ledger's estate, two final films and his celebrated Brokeback performance ensure the money will keep flowing.}}</ref><ref name=Squires>{{cite news|author=Nick Squires|title=Heath Ledger 'fathered a secret love child'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1583417/Heath-Ledger-'fathered-a-secret-love-child'.html|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK|date=1 April 2008|accessdate=6 August 2008 |quote=If the claims are proved to be true, Ledger's multi-million pound estate would have to be divided between the child he fathered in his teens and his two-year-old daughter, Matilda Rose, whose mother is Hollywood actress Michelle Williams. ... The actor's parents, Kim and Sally Ledger, have declined to comment on the reports [based on comments by other family members, including his uncle Haydn Ledger]. }}</ref> A few days later, reports citing telephone interviews with Ledger's uncles Haydn and Mike Ledger and the family of the other little girl, published in ''[[OK!]]'' and ''[[Us Weekly]]'', \"denied\" those \"claims\", with Ledger's uncles and the little girl's mother and stepfather describing them as unfounded \"rumors\" distorted and exaggerated by the media.<ref name=OKLedger>{{cite news|title=Denied: No Love Child for Heath Ledger |url=http://www.okmagazine.com/news/view/5697 |work=okmagazine.com ([[OK!]] Magazine, Northern & Shell North America Ltd.) |date=3 April 2008 |accessdate=6 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080623232323/http://www.okmagazine.com/news/view/5697 |archivedate=23 June 2008 }}</ref><ref name=UsLedger>{{cite news|title=Heath Ledger's Uncle: Love Child Reports Are 'Absolutely Berserk'|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/heath_ledgers_uncle_love_child_reports_are_absolutely_berserk|work=usmagazine.com ([[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media LLC]])|date=3 April 2008|accessdate=6 August 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080406232610/http://www.usmagazine.com/heath_ledgers_uncle_love_child_reports_are_absolutely_berserk <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 6 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 July 2008, Fife-Yeomans reported further, via Australian [[News Limited]], that \"While Ledger left everything to his parents and three sisters, it is understood they have legal advice that under Western Australia law, Matilda Rose is entitled to the [[lion's share]]\" of his estate; its [[executor]]s, Kim Ledger's former business colleague Robert John Collins and [[Geraldton]] accountant William Mark Dyson, \"have applied for [[probate]] in the [[Supreme Court of Western Australia|West Australian Supreme Court]] in [[Perth]], advertising for '[[creditor]]s and other persons' having claims on the estate to lodge them by 11 August 2008 ... to ensure all debts are paid before the estate is distributed....\"<ref name=FifeYeomans2>{{cite news|author=Janet Fife-Yeomans |title=Entertainment: Heath Ledger's Daughter Matilda's Estate Claim Decision |url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/story/0,26278,24022070-5015788,00.html |work=news.com.au |publisher=[[News Limited]] |date=15 July 2008 |accessdate=10 August 2008 |quote=[Matilda Rose's] mother, actor Michelle Williams, will have to officially lodge a claim with the court supported by an affidavit which could end up in the [[public domain]], legal experts said. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080802022149/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/story/0%2C26278%2C24022070-5015788%2C00.html |archivedate=2 August 2008 }}</ref> According to this report by Fife-Yeomans, earlier reports citing Ledger's uncles,<ref name=FoxNewsUncles /> and subsequent reports citing Ledger's father, which do not include his actual posthumous earnings, \"his entire fortune, mostly held in Australian trusts, is likely to be worth up to [[Australian dollar|$]]20&nbsp;million.\"<ref name=FifeYeomans2 /><ref name=Eng>{{cite news|author=Joyce Eng |title=Heath Ledger's Daughter to Inherit Estate |url=http://community.tvguide.com/blog-entry/TVGuide-News-Blog/Todays-News/Heath-Ledgers-Estate/800047540 |work=TV Guide |publisher=OpenGate Capital |date=29 September 2008 |accessdate=11 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202020123/http://community.tvguide.com/blog-entry/TVGuide-News-Blog/Todays-News/Heath-Ledgers-Estate/800047540 |archivedate=2 December 2008 }}</ref><ref name=APAOL>{{cite news|url=http://www.aol.com.au/celebrity/story/Ledger's-daughter-to-inherit-late-actor's-estate/1054531/index.html |agency=Associated Press |title=Ledger's Daughter to Inherit Late Actor's Estate |work=AOL Australia Celebrity Channel |date=29 September 2008 |accessdate=11 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219001545/http://www.aol.com.au/celebrity/story/Ledger%27s-daughter-to-inherit-late-actor%27s-estate/1054531/index.html |archivedate=19 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 September 2008, Ledger's father Kim stated that \"the family has agreed to leave the US$16.3&nbsp;million fortune to Matilda,\" adding: \"There is no claim. Our family has gifted everything to Matilda.\"<ref name=Eng /><ref name=APAOL /> In October 2008, ''[[Forbes]]'' estimated Ledger's annual earnings from October 2007 through October 2008 \u2013 including his posthumous share of ''The Dark Knight''{{'}}s gross income of \"US$1&nbsp;billion in box office revenue worldwide\" \u2013 as \"US$20&nbsp;million\".<ref name=Nichols>{{cite news|author=Michelle Nichols|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/DarkKnight/idUSTRE49S54I20081029|title=Elvis Ranked Top-earning Dead Celebrity|agency=Reuters.com|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]|date=29 October 2008|accessdate=10 December 2008|quote=Forbes.com said it spoke to experts and sources inside the dead celebrities' estates and researched gross earnings, before taxes, management fees and other costs, from the period of October 2007 to October 2008 to come up with the rankings.}} Based on its estimates, Nichols reports, ''Forbes.com'' ranks Ledger as third among the world's highest-earning deceased celebrities for that year, following [[Elvis Presley]] (1) and [[Charles M. Schulz]] (2).</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\n===Memorial tributes and services===\n[[File:LedgerMemorial.jpg|right|thumb|180px|Memorial for Ledger, outside 421 Broome Street, [[SoHo]], Manhattan, 23 January 2008|alt=Dark doorway and doorstep with section of footpath. On the lower part of the dark door is a partly obscured Australian flag with dark blue background; red and white crosses on top left, large white star underneath and three white stars at the right with others obscured. Obscuring the right side of the flag is a white sheet with light blue writing, \"Love + Miss You Always Heath\" with two red hearts nearby, other writing includes \"I'll never quit you\" in darker blue, more writing is indistinct. This sheet also has six photos of a man. Above the flag, on the door is a smaller sheet with a photo of a man and indistinct writing below. On the doorstep and section of footpath are some 14 groups of flowers wrapped in plastic or paper, together with nine or so cards, five or six lit candles, and more photos. On the right side is a straw hat.]]\nAs the news of Ledger's death became public, throughout the night of 22 January 2008, and the next day, media crews, mourners, fans, and other onlookers began gathering outside his apartment building, with some leaving flowers or other memorial tributes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-ledger23jan23,0,3455258.story|title=Ledger's death is a shock to Hollywood, fans|last=Boucher|first=Geoff|first2=Matea |last2=Gold |first3= Paul |last3=Lieberman|date=23 January 2008|work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=2 April 2009|quote=Minutes after the news of Ledger's death broke, several hundred people gathered outside the Broome Street apartment building where Ledger had been living&nbsp;... television crews and area residents were joined by fans, including some Brooklyn acting students.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7204439.stm|title=Stars pay tribute to Heath Ledger|date=23 January 2008|work=BBC News |accessdate=2 April 2009|quote=Fans have been leaving flowers and candles outside Ledger's apartment in the SoHo district.}}</ref>\n\nThe next day, at 10:50&nbsp;am [[Time in Australia|Australian time]], Ledger's parents and sister appeared outside his mother's house in [[Applecross, Western Australia|Applecross]], a riverside suburb of [[Perth]], and read a short statement to the media expressing their grief and desire for privacy.<ref name=DTfam>{{cite news |title=Heath Ledger Loved Life, Family Tell |url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,23096240-5001021,00.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=Australia |date=23 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2008}}</ref> Within the next few days, memorial tributes were communicated by family members; the [[Prime Minister of Australia]], [[Kevin Rudd]]; the [[Premier of Western Australia|Deputy Premier of Western Australia]], [[Eric Ripper]]; [[Warner Bros.]] (distributor of ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'') and thousands of Ledger's fans around the world.<ref name=PM>{{cite news|author=Office of the [[Prime Minister of Australia]] |title=Media Release |url=http://www.pm.gov.au/news/releases/2008/media_release_00012.cfm |accessdate=5 February 2008 |date=22 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080210001805/http://www.pm.gov.au/news/releases/2008/media_release_00012.cfm |archivedate=10 February 2008 }}</ref><ref name=Pendrill>{{cite news |first=Lisa |last=Pendrill |title=Heath's Family Writes of Heartache |url=http://www.perthnow.com.au/heath-familys-new-tribute/story-fna7dq6e-1111115398106 |work=The Sunday Telegraph |location=Australia |date=25 January 2008 |accessdate=2 February 2008}}</ref><ref name=WB>{{cite news |author=Warner Bros. |url=http://thedarkknight.warnerbros.com/HeathMemorial.html |title=Heath Memorial |date=25 January 2008 |accessdate=5 February 2008 |publisher=Warner Brothers|author-link=Warner Bros }}</ref><ref name=Online>{{cite news |title=Online Community Pays Tribute to Heath Ledger |url=http://www.901am.com/2008/online-community-pays-tribute-to-heath-ledger.html |work=901am.com |date=25 January 2008 |accessdate=6 February 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100411013042/http://www.901am.com/2008/online-community-pays-tribute-to-heath-ledger.html |archive-date=11 April 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSeveral actors made statements expressing their sorrow at Ledger's death, including [[Daniel Day-Lewis]], who dedicated his [[Screen Actors Guild Award]] to him, saying that he was inspired by Ledger's acting; Day-Lewis praised Ledger's performances in ''[[Monster's Ball]]'' and ''[[Brokeback Mountain]]'', describing the latter as \"unique, perfect\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Amy |last=Diluna |first2=Joe |last2=Neumaier |title=Daniel Day-Lewis Honors Heath Ledger during Screen Actors Guild Awards |work=New York Daily News |date=27 January 2008 |accessdate=16 February 2008 |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/2008/01/27/2008-01-27_daniel_daylewis_honors_heath_ledger_duri.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Catherine|last=Elsworth|title=Daniel Day Lewis, Julie Christie win at Screen Actors Guild Awards|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3670802/Daniel-Day-Lewis-Julie-Christie-win-at-Screen-Actors-Guild-Awards.html|date=28 January 2008|accessdate=3 December 2009|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK }}</ref> [[Verne Troyer]], who was working with Ledger on ''The Imaginarium of Doctor Parnassus'' at the time of his death, had a heart shape, an exact duplicate of a symbol that Ledger scrawled on a piece of paper with his email address, tattooed on his hand in remembrance of Ledger because Ledger \"had made such an impression on [him]\".<ref>{{cite episode |title=Celebrity Big Brother |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1350648/ |series=Celebrity Big Brother 2009 |serieslink=Celebrity Big Brother 2009 (UK) |airdate=2009-01-06 |season=2009 |number=Day 4}}</ref> British indie band [[Kasabian]] paid tribute to Ledger in their song 'Vlad the Impaler', with the line \"Joker, meet you on the other side\". Singer [[Tom Meighan]] often changes the word \"Joker\" to either \"Ledger\", or the names of recently deceased celebrities.\n\nOn 1 February, in her first public statement after Ledger's death, Michelle Williams expressed her heartbreak and described Ledger's spirit as surviving in their daughter.<ref>{{cite news |title=Michelle Williams: Heath Ledger Has Broken My Heart |url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,23147754-5001021,00.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=Australia |date=1 February 2008 |accessdate=1 February 2008}}</ref><ref name=People>{{cite news|title=Michelle Williams Breaks Silence on Heath's Death |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20175486,00.html|work=People |date=1 February 2008 |accessdate=2 February 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter attending private memorial ceremonies in Los Angeles, Ledger's family members returned with his body to [[Perth]].<ref name=Silverman>{{cite news|first=Stephen M. |last=Silverman |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20176033,00.html |title=Heath Ledger's Family Heads Home |work=People |date=4 February 2008 |accessdate=4 February 2008}}</ref><ref name=Rodriguez>{{cite news |first=Brenda |last=Rodriguez |title=A Sorrowful Return to Australia for Heath Ledger's Family |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20176124,00.html |work=People |date=5 February 2008 |accessdate=5 February 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 February, a memorial service attended by several hundred invited guests was held at [[Penrhos College, Perth|Penrhos College]], attracting considerable [[mass media|press]] attention; afterward Ledger's body was cremated at [[Fremantle Cemetery]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www2.mcb.wa.gov.au/NameSearch/details.php?id=FC00052109|title=Heath Ledger's death record|last=|first=|date=|website=Metropolitan Cemeteries Board|access-date=}}</ref> followed by a private service attended by only 10 closest family members,<ref name=Kent>{{Cite news |first=Melissa |last=Kent |title=Tears, Tributes Accompany Heath Ledger to His Final Rest |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2008/02/09/1202234231953.html?from=top5 |work=The Age | location=Melbourne |date=9 February 2008 |accessdate=21 April 2008}}</ref><ref name=funeral>{{cite news|title=Heath Ledger Farewelled at Perth Funeral |url=http://www.news.com.au/story/0,23599,23184908-2,00.html |work=news.com.au |date=9 February 2008 |accessdate=9 February 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080212134905/http://www.news.com.au/story/0%2C23599%2C23184908-2%2C00.html |archivedate=12 February 2008 }}</ref><ref name=IHT>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |title=Reports: Michelle Williams Arrives in Perth for Heath Ledger's Funeral |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/02/06/arts/AS-A-E-CEL-Australia-Ledger.php |work=International Herald Tribune |date=6 February 2008 |accessdate=7 February 2008}}</ref> with his ashes interred later in a family plot at [[Karrakatta Cemetery]], next to two of his grandparents.<ref name=Rodriguez /><ref name=CazzalinoConnolly>{{cite news |first=Michelle |last=Cazzalino |first2=Ellen |last2=Connolly |title=Last, Sad Farewell for Heath |work=The Sunday Telegraph |location=Australia |page=5 |date=10 February 2008}}</ref><ref name=Karrakatta>{{cite web|title=Summary of Record Information: Heath Andrew Ledger |url=http://www.mcb.wa.gov.au/NameSearch/details.php?id=FC00052109 |publisher=Metropolitan Cemeteries Board, Western Australia |accessdate=7 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218013051/http://www.mcb.wa.gov.au/NameSearch/details.php?id=FC00052109 |archivedate=18 December 2008 }}</ref> Later that night, his family and friends gathered for a [[Wake (ceremony)|wake]] on [[Cottesloe, Western Australia|Cottesloe Beach]].<ref name=swim>{{cite news|first=Michelle |last=Cazzulino |first2=Stephen |last2=Corby |title=Star Swim at Heath Ledger's Farewell: Ledger Wake Held in Perth |work=news.com.au |date=10 February 2008 |accessdate=9 February 2008 |url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/story/0,26278,23189271-10388,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080211091825/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/story/0%2C26278%2C23189271-10388%2C00.html |archivedate=11 February 2008 }}</ref><ref name=beach>{{cite news|first=Wendy |last=Caccetta |first2=Nicole |last2=Cox |title=Beach Tribute to Heath Ledger |url=http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,23184885-952,00.html |work=[[The Courier-Mail]] |date=10 February 2008 |accessdate=9 February 2008}}</ref><ref name=swim2>{{cite news |first=Michelle |last=Cazzulino |first2=Stephen |last2=Corby |title=Michelle Williams Swims at Heath Ledger's Wake |url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,23188937-5001021,00.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=Australia |date=10 February 2008 |accessdate=10 February 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, the [[State Theatre Centre of Western Australia]] in Ledger's home town of [[Perth]] named a 575-seat theatre the Heath Ledger Theatre after him. For the opening of the theatre, Ledger's [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] was on display in the theatre's foyer along with his [[Joker (character)|Joker]] costume.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/arts-books/state-theatre-centre-opens-in-perth-honouring-heath-ledger/story-fn7euh6j-1225996093685|title=Act of love for Ledger theatre|publisher=|date=28 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Bon Iver]]'s \"Perth\" was inspired by Heath Ledger.<ref name=\"rs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/i-am-heath-ledger-10-things-we-learned-from-spike-tv-doc-w482581|title='I Am Heath Ledger': 10 Things We Learned From Spike TV Doc|last=Newman|first=Jason|date=18 May 2017|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> [[Justin Vernon]], the lead singer and songwriter of the American indie folk band, revealed back in 2011 that he had begun working on the song in 2008 and was scheduled to meet with a music video director who was good friends with Ledger, Matt Amato. \"The first thing I worked on, the riff and the beginning melodies, was the first song on the record, 'Perth,'\" Vernon told ''[[Exclaim!]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/bon-ivers-perth-was-inspired-by-heath-ledger-it-makes-the-song-so-much-more-poignant-53267|title=Bon Iver's 'Perth' Was Inspired By Heath Ledger & It Makes The Song So Much More Poignant|last=Brayson|first=Johnny|date=25 April 2017|work=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> Amato was directing the band's \"The Wolves (Act I & II)\" music video the day that Ledger died. \"It was no longer about just making a Bon Iver music video anymore,\" Vernon says. \"This was now our chance to be there with Matt as he grieved. It was a three-day wake.\" Amato told Vernon stories about Ledger that eventually became the inspiration for \"Perth,\" the opening track to the band's second studio album ''[[Bon Iver (album)|Bon Iver, Bon Iver]]'' (2011).<ref name=\"rs\"/>\n\n===Method and style===\n[[File:March 2006 cover of Rolling Stone magazine featuring Heath Ledger.png|thumb|190px|left|Ledger on the March 2006 cover of ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'']]\n{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote=\"You know when you see the preachers down South? And they grab a believer and they go, 'Bwoom! I touch you with the hand of God!' And they believe so strongly, they're on the ground shaking and spitting. And fuck's sake, that's the power of belief... Now, I don't believe in Jesus, but I believe in my performance. And if you can understand that the power of belief is one of the great tools of our time and that a lot of acting comes from it, you can do anything.\"|source=\u2014Ledger, during the interview with ''Rolling Stone'' in 2006, on belief, power and acting.<ref name=\"www.rollingstone.com\" />}}\nPortraying a variety of roles, from [[romantic hero]]es to the [[Sympathetic character|reluctantly oppressed]], Ledger created a hodgepodge of characters that are deliberately unlike one another, stating \"I feel like I am wasting my time if I repeat myself\". He also reflected on his inability to be happy with his work, \"I feel the same thing about everything I do. The day I say, 'It's good' is the day I should start doing something else.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/04/movies/moviesspecial/04lyal.html|title=Heath Ledger \u2013 I'm Not There -|last=Lyall|first=Sarah|date=4 November 2007|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> Ledger liked to wait between jobs so that he would start creatively hungry on new projects.<ref name=\"Nolan. Christopher 2008\">Nolan. Christopher. CHARISMA AS NATURAL AS GRAVITY. Published 26 January 2008.</ref> In his own words, acting was about harnessing \"the infinite power of belief,\"<ref name=\"www.rollingstone.com\">Lipsky. David. [https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/heath-ledgers-lonesome-trail-20130325 Heath Ledger's Lonesome Trail], ROLLINGSTONE. From Mars 23, 2006. Retrieved on 02 Mars 2016.</ref> thus using belief as a tool for creating.\n\nDirectors who have worked with the actor praised him for his creativity, [[seriousness]] and [[intuition]]. \"I've never felt as old as I did watching Heath explore his talents,\" ''The Dark Knight'' director Christopher Nolan has written, expressing amazement over the actor's working process, genuine curiosity and charisma.<ref name=\"Nolan. Christopher 2008\" /> [[Marc Forster]], who directed Ledger in ''Monster's Ball'', complimented him as taking the job \"very seriously\", being disciplined, observant, and [[Nous|understanding and intuitive]]. In 2007, director Todd Haynes compared Ledger's presence to actor [[James Dean]], casting Ledger as Robbie Clarke, a fictive personification of Bob Dylan in ''I'm Not There''. Drawing on the similar characteristics between the actors, Haynes further highlighted Ledger's \"precocious seriousness\" and intuition. He also felt that Ledger had a rare maturity beyond his years.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Ledger, however, disconnected himself and acting from [[Perfectionism (psychology)|perfectionism]]. \"I'm always gonna pull myself apart and dissect [the work]. I mean, there's no such thing as perfection in what [actors] do. [[pornographic film actor|Pornos]] are more perfect than we are, because they're actually fucking.\"<ref name=\"www.rollingstone.com\" />\n\n\"Some people find their shtick,\" Ledger reflected on the categorisation of style. \"I never figured out who 'Heath Ledger' is on film: 'This is what you expect when you hire me, and it will be recognisable'... People always feel compelled to sum you up, to presume that they have you and can describe you. That's fine. But there are so many stories inside of me and a lot I want to achieve outside of one flat note.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Posthumous films and awards===\n{{further||List of accolades received by The Dark Knight}}\nLedger's death affected the marketing campaign for [[Christopher Nolan]]'s ''The Dark Knight'' (2008)<ref name=Halbfinger2 /><ref name=Halbfinger /> and also both the production and marketing of [[Terry Gilliam]]'s film ''[[The Imaginarium of Doctor Parnassus]]'', with both directors intending to celebrate and pay tribute to his work in these films.<ref name=Halbfinger /><ref name=Kilpatrick /><ref name=CNNBind>{{cite news|title=Ledger's Death Puts Last Films in a Bind|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Movies/01/24/ledger.films/index.html|work=CNN |date=24 January 2008|accessdate=30 January 2008}}</ref><ref name=Carroll>{{cite news|first=Larry |last=Carroll|title='Dark Knight' Stars, Director Want Film To 'Celebrate' Heath Ledger's Work|url=http://www.mtv.com/movies/news/articles/1583563/story.jhtml|work=MTV|date=18 March 2008|accessdate=27 April 2008}}</ref> Although Gilliam temporarily suspended production on the latter film,<ref name=Kilpatrick /> he expressed determination to \"salvage\" it, perhaps using [[computer-generated imagery]] (CGI), and dedicated it to Ledger.<ref name=Stoynoff>{{cite news |first=Natasha |last=Stoynoff |title=Show Will Go on for Heath's Last Movie, Says CoStar|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20174404,00.html |work=People |date=28 January 2008 |accessdate=5 February 2008}}</ref><ref name=WENN3>{{cite news|author=WENN (World Entertainment News Network)|title=Gilliam Trying to Save Last Ledger Film|url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/Gilliam_Trying_to_Save_Last_Ledger_Film/5055155 |work=Hollywood.com|date=28 January 2008|accessdate=2 February 2008<!--needs replaced archive link; can't use the archive dot is service any more-->}}</ref><ref name=Brady>{{cite news|first=Matt |last=Brady |title=Heath Ledger Dies |url=http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=144093 |work=[[Newsarama]] |date=23 January 2008 |accessdate=22 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100411063851/http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=144093 |archivedate=11 April 2010 }}</ref> In February 2008, as a \"memorial tribute to the man many have called one of the best actors of his generation,\" [[Johnny Depp]], [[Jude Law]], and [[Colin Farrell]] signed on to take over Ledger's role, becoming multiple incarnations of his character, Tony, transformed in this \"magical re-telling of the [[Faust]] story\".<ref name=AICN>{{cite news |author=Moriarty|url=https://aintitcool.com/node/35623 |title=AICN exclusive! We Know Who's Paying Tribute To Heath Ledger in Dr. Parnassus Now!|work=[[Ain't It Cool News]] |date=15 February 2008|accessdate=17 February 2008|authorlink=Drew McWeeny}}</ref><ref name=Adler2>{{cite news|first=Shawn |last=Adler |title=Heath Ledger's Final Film To Go Forward \u2013 With Johnny Depp, Jude Law, Colin Farrell in His Role |publisher=MTV |url=http://www.mtv.ca/news/article.jhtml?id=7086 |date=15 February 2008 |accessdate=15 February 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511152754/http://www.mtv.ca/news/article.jhtml?id=7086 |archivedate=11 May 2011 }}</ref><ref name=NYTAB>{{cite news|title=Arts Briefly: Three Actors Replace Heath Ledger|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/19/arts/19arts-THREEACTORSR_BRF.html|work=The New York Times |date=19 February 2008|accessdate=19 February 2008}}</ref> The three actors donated their fees for the film to Ledger's and Williams's daughter.<ref name=BBCParnassus>{{cite news|title=Trio Give Fees to Ledger's Child|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7570056.stm|work=BBC News |date=19 August 2008|accessdate=20 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nSpeaking of editing ''The Dark Knight,'' on which Ledger had completed his work in October 2007, Nolan recalled, \"It was tremendously emotional, right when he passed, having to go back in and look at him every day. ... But the truth is, I feel very lucky to have something productive to do, to have a performance that he was very, very proud of, and that he had entrusted to me to finish.\"<ref name=Carroll /> All of Ledger's scenes appear as he completed them in the filming; in editing the film, Nolan added no \"digital effects\" to alter Ledger's actual performance posthumously.<ref name=Brown>{{cite journal |first=Scott |last=Brown|title=Dark Knight Director Shuns Digital Effects for the Real Thing |url=https://www.wired.com/entertainment/hollywood/magazine/16-07/ff_darknight?currentPage=all|journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |issue=24 June 2008|accessdate=24 June 2008|date=23 June 2008}}</ref> Nolan dedicated the film in part to Ledger's memory, as well as to the memory of technician Conway Wickliffe, who was killed during a car accident while preparing one of the film's stunts.<ref name=Hough>{{cite news|title=Dark Knight Dedicated to Ledger |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7477095.stm|work=BBC News |date=27 June 2008|accessdate=27 June 2008|quote=The special tribute reads: 'In memory of our friends Heath Ledger and Conway Wickliffe'.}}</ref>\n\n[[File:HeathJoker.png|right|thumb|180px|Ledger's performance as [[Joker (The Dark Knight)|The Joker]] in the film earned him the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]], making him the first actor to win an Oscar for a comic-book movie.]]\nReleased in July 2008, ''The Dark Knight'' broke several box office records and received both popular and critical accolades, especially with regard to Ledger's performance as the Joker.<ref name=DKBOM>{{cite web|first=Brandon |last=Gray|title=News: 'Dark Knight' Begins Smashingly |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2504&p=s.htm|work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=23 July 2008|accessdate=2 August 2008}}</ref> Even film critic [[David Denby (film critic)|David Denby]], who does not praise the film overall in his pre-release review in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', evaluates Ledger's work highly, describing his performance as both \"sinister and frightening\" and Ledger as \"mesmerising in every scene\", concluding: \"His performance is a heroic, unsettling final act: this young actor looked into the abyss.\"<ref name=Denby>{{cite journal|url= http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/cinema/2008/07/21/080721crci_cinema_denby|title=The Current Cinema: Past Shock: '' 'The Dark Knight' and 'WALL-E' ''|last=Denby|first= David|journal=[[The New Yorker]]|issue=21 July 2008 |accessdate=17 July 2008|pages=92\u201393|quote=When Ledger wields a knife, he is thoroughly terrifying (do not, despite the [[Television content rating systems#United States|PG-13]] rating, bring the children), and, as you're watching him, you can't help wondering\u2014in a response that admittedly lies outside film criticism\u2014how badly he messed himself up in order to play the role this way.|authorlink= David Denby (film critic)}} (Postdated)</ref> Attempting to dispel widespread speculations that Ledger's performance as the Joker had in any way led to his death (as Denby and others suggest), Ledger's co-star and friend [[Christian Bale]], who played opposite him as [[Batman]], has stressed that, as an actor, Ledger greatly enjoyed meeting the challenges of creating that role, an experience that Ledger himself described as \"the most fun I've ever had, or probably ever will have, playing a character\".<ref name=Halbfinger2 /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2008/03/07/1204780065888.html|title=Could it be any darker?|last=Halbfinger|first=David|date=8 March 2008|work=The Sydney Morning Herald |page=2|accessdate=8 October 2009}}</ref> Terry Gilliam also refuted the claims that playing the Joker made him crazy, calling it \"absolute nonsense\" and going on to say, \"Heath was so solid. His feet were on the ground and he was the least neurotic person I've ever met.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://the-talks.com/interviews/terry-gilliam/|title=Terry Gilliam \u2013 The Talks|work=the-talks.com|accessdate=5 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nLedger received numerous awards for his Joker role in ''The Dark Knight''. On 10 November 2008, he was nominated for two [[People's Choice Awards]] related to his work on the film, \"Best Ensemble Cast\" and \"Best Onscreen Match-Up\" (shared with Christian Bale), and Ledger won an award for \"Match-Up\" in the ceremony aired live on CBS in January 2009.<ref name=PeoplesChoice>{{cite news|first=Jessica |last=Herndon|title=Britney Spears, Heath Ledger Get People's Choice Nods|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20239377,00.html|work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=10 November 2008|accessdate=11 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 December 2008, it was announced that Ledger had been nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]] for his performance as the Joker in ''The Dark Knight''; he subsequently won the award at the [[66th Golden Globe Awards]] ceremony telecast on [[NBC]] on 11 January 2009 with ''Dark Knight'' director Christopher Nolan accepting on his behalf.<ref name=PeopleLedger /><ref name=accolades>{{cite news|url=https://latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-globesstory12-2009jan12,0,6073218.story|title=Accolades flow after Heath Ledger's 'Dark Knight' win|last=Abramowitz |first=Rachel|date=12 January 2009|work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=12 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nFilm critics, co-stars [[Maggie Gyllenhaal]] and [[Michael Caine]] and many of Ledger's colleagues in the film community joined Bale in calling for and predicting a nomination for the 2008 [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] in recognition of Ledger's achievement in ''The Dark Knight.''<ref name=NHSmith>{{cite web|first=Nina H\u00e4mmerling |last=Smith |title=Movie News: Ledger's Knight Costars Call for Posthumous Oscar |url=http://community.tvguide.com/blog-entry/TVGuide-Editors-Blog/Movie-News/Heath-Ledger-News/800044048 |work=[[TV Guide]] |date=28 July 2008 |accessdate=11 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212054811/http://community.tvguide.com/blog-entry/TVGuide-Editors-Blog/Movie-News/Heath-Ledger-News/800044048 |archivedate=12 December 2008 }}</ref> Ledger's subsequent nomination was announced on 22 January 2009, the anniversary of his death.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2009/01/22/heath-ledger-remembered-on-first-anniversary-of-his-death/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090127034033/http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2009/01/22/heath-ledger-remembered-on-first-anniversary-of-his-death/|archivedate=27 January 2009|title=Heath Ledger Remembered on First Anniversary of His Death|last=Kreps|first=Daniel|date=22 January 2009|work=Rolling Stone |accessdate=13 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nLedger went on to win the Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor, becoming the second person to win a posthumous Academy Award for acting (after fellow Australian actor [[Peter Finch]], who won for 1976's ''[[Network (1976 film)|Network]]''), as well as the first comic-book movie actor to win an Oscar for their acting. Ledger's family attended the [[81st Academy Awards|ceremony]] on 22 February 2009, with his parents and sister accepting the award on stage on his behalf.<ref name=\"Heath Ledger Oscar\">{{cite news|url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/awards/oscars/la-et-oscarledger23-2009feb23,0,5458027.story|title=For Heath Ledger, a bittersweet salute | last = Johnson | first=Reed | date=23 February 2009 |work=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Publishing|accessdate=5 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=Posthumous>{{cite news |url=https://www.today.com/popculture/slumdog-millionaire-fulfills-its-oscar-destiny-wbna29332714 |title='Slumdog Millionaire' fulfills its Oscar destiny|publisher=[[Today.com]]|agency=Associated Press |date=23 February 2009 |accessdate=23 February 2009}}</ref> Following talks with the Ledger family in Australia, the Academy determined that Ledger's daughter, Matilda Rose, would own the award. However, due to Matilda's age, she will not gain full ownership of the statuette until her eighteenth birthday in 2023.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pond|first=Steve|title=If Ledger Wins, Oscar Goes To Daughter|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/if-ledger-wins-oscar-goes-to-daughter/|work=CBS News|publisher=CBS Corporation|accessdate=7 June 2013|date=18 February 2009}}</ref> Her mother, Michelle Williams, will hold the statuette in trust for Matilda until that time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/100747/why-can-t-li-l-matilda-have-heath-s-potential-oscar | title=Why Can't Li'l Matilda Have Heath's (Potential) Oscar? | date= 19 February 2009|first=Leslie |last=Gornstein |work= E!|publisher=NBCUniversal|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April 2017, a trailer was released for the documentary ''[[I Am Heath Ledger]]'' which was released on 3 May 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last1=France|first1=Lisa Respers|title=Heath Ledger as you've never seen him|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/04/05/entertainment/heath-ledger-documentary/|website=CNN}}</ref> It features archival footage of Ledger and interviews.<ref name=\"Iam\">{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Ashley|title=Heath Ledger Documentary Trailer Previews Footage Shot by Late Actor|url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/heath-ledger-documentary-trailer-previews-footage-shot-by-late-actor-991323|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Clowning Around]]''\n| Orphan Clown\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1997\n| ''[[Blackrock (film)|Blackrock]]''\n| Toby Ackland\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Paws (film)|Paws]]''\n| Oberon\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1999\n| ''[[10 Things I Hate About You]]''\n| Patrick Verona\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Two Hands (1999 film)|Two Hands]]''\n| Jimmy\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Patriot (2000 film)|The Patriot]]''\n| Gabriel Martin\